# State which project rules apply when a chat begins

Cursor injects project rules from **`.cursor/rules/ai-rules/*.mdc`**. This file is **`alwaysApply: true`**, so it should be in context whenever that pack is installed and not renamed to **`.mdc.disabled`**.

## Non-negotiable (user-visible)

For the **first assistant message in this chat** that responds to the user’s prompt (not a hidden tool-only step), you **must** put the following **at the very top** of the markdown you show the user—before explanations, plans, or code. You may use **one short sentence** (≤ 20 words) before it only if you are acknowledging the request.

Use this **exact** heading (three hashes, exact spelling):

### Active project rules

Immediately under that heading, add a **compact bullet list**. Each bullet must be:

`- **`filename.mdc`** — one short phrase (from its `description` or obvious purpose).`

**Minimum rows** (skip a row only if that rule is clearly disabled, e.g. only `*.mdc.disabled` exists and no active `.mdc`):

- `state-active-project-rules.mdc`
- `write-clean-code.mdc`
- `reuse-code-before-duplicating.mdc`
- `organize-repository-by-feature.mdc`
- `secure-code-data-and-dependencies.mdc`
- `prefer-lts-stable-runtimes-and-libraries.mdc`
- `update-changelog-for-notable-changes.mdc`
- `append-and-deduplicate-requirements.mdc`
- `verify-syntax-and-fix-before-finishing.mdc`
- `remove-dead-code-and-unused-files.mdc`

Also list **`evolve-rules-when-codebase-patterns-change.mdc`** only if it is active (not stored as `.mdc.disabled`).

Add **glob-scoped** rules from this folder when the user’s open files, attachments, or task clearly match their `globs` (e.g. Markdown work → `use-this-format-for-markdown-files.mdc`; editing rules under `ai-rules` → `write-cursor-rules-for-this-project.mdc`, `maintain-cursor-rules.mdc`).

Add any rule the user **@-mentioned**.

If you are unsure which glob rules apply, say so in **one** short line after the list—do not skip the list.

## Later messages in the same chat

Do **not** repeat the full block on every back-and-forth. Repeat it when the user starts a **clearly new** topic, a **new Agent/Composer run**, or asks what rules apply.

Keep the list **short**—filenames and phrases only, not full rule bodies.
